We use a dynamic programming approach to solve the problem. We create a 26-dimensional array (one dimension for each character in the alphabet) and fill it with the minimum number of steps needed to convert t to an anagram of s. We iterate through the characters of s and t, and for each pair of characters, we find the minimum number of steps needed to convert t to an anagram of s. We return the minimum number of steps for the first character of t.

This solution has a time complexity of O(n) because we only iterate through the characters of s and t once. The space complexity is O(n) because we need to store the minimum number of steps for each character in the array. The energy implications are low because the solution only involves simple string operations and does not consume significant energy.

